#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:1
msgid "Comments"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:3
msgid "Explain why, not what (`explain-why`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:5
msgid ""
"Comments should explain the intent behind the code, not restate what the "
"code does. If a comment merely paraphrases the code, it adds noise without "
"insight."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:10
msgid ""
"If a comment is needed to explain what code does, first try to rewrite the "
"code. Do not write good comments to compensate for bad code — rewrite it to "
"be straightforward."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:15
msgid ""
"See also: _The Art of Readable Code_, Chapter 6 \"Knowing What to Comment\"; "
"PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:20
msgid "Document design decisions (`design-decisions`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:22
msgid ""
"When the code makes a non-obvious choice — a particular data structure, a "
"locking strategy, a deviation from Linux behavior — add a comment explaining "
"the rationale and any alternatives considered. Design-decision comments "
"(\"director's commentary\") are the most valuable kind of comment."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:31
msgid ""
"// We use a radix tree rather than a HashMap\n"
"// because lookups must be O(log n) worst-case\n"
"// for the page fault handler.\n"
"// A HashMap gives O(1) amortized\n"
"// but O(n) worst-case due to rehashing,\n"
"// which is unacceptable on the page fault path.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:39
msgid ""
"See also: PR [\\#2265](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"pull/2265#discussion_r2266220943) and [\\#2050](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/pull/2050#discussion_r2224106025)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:43
msgid "Cite specifications and algorithm sources (`cite-sources`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:45
msgid ""
"When implementing behavior defined by an external specification or a non-"
"trivial algorithm, cite the source: the relevant POSIX section, Linux man "
"page, hardware reference manual, or academic paper."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/for-maintainability/comments.md:52
msgid ""
"/// Maximum number of bytes guaranteed to be written to a pipe atomically.\n"
"///\n"
"/// For more details, see the description of `PIPE_BUF` in\n"
"/// <https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/pipe.7.html>.\n"
msgstr ""
